Veea builds secure edge AI and infrastructure systems for enterprise deployments. For this hackathon, Veea introduces Lobster Trap, a deep prompt inspection and policy enforcement layer designed to help developers build secure, observable, and production-ready AI agents.

Challenge:

Build the trust layer enterprise security teams will actually sign off on.

Agents now read files, hit APIs, send messages, and trigger actions inside production systems, but the guardrails have not kept up. A single manipulated prompt can leak credentials, exfiltrate data, or trigger the wrong action while most teams still lack visibility into what their agents are doing.

Build guardrails, observability, access control, audit, or red-team tooling where policy enforcement and conversation-layer security are first-class citizens, not an afterthought.

Participants are encouraged to build projects involving:

• Prompt injection and exfiltration detection
• Guardrails and policy enforcement for AI agents
• Access control and permission systems
• Agent observability and audit tooling
• Red-team and adversarial testing
• Governance dashboards and explainability tooling
• Multi-agent security frameworks
Bonus points for measurable risk reduction, blocked attacks, caught exfiltration, declared-versus-detected intent mismatches, or audit trails a regulator could read.

Technology

Lobster Trap is a deep prompt inspection (DPI) proxy that sits between your agents and any OpenAI-compatible LLM backend, enforcing P4-style firewall rules on every prompt and response without changing your application code.

Key capabilities:

• Drop-in deployment: Works with OpenAI-compatible APIs including Ollama, vLLM, llama.cpp, OpenAI, Anthropic, and Gemini via proxy.
• Real DPI, not vibes: Extracts structured metadata including intent category, risk scoring, credentials, PII, injections, exfiltration patterns, target paths, domains, and risky commands.
• Programmable policy: YAML-based rules with first-match-wins logic and actions including ALLOW, DENY, LOG, HUMAN_REVIEW, QUARANTINE, and RATE_LIMIT.
• Bidirectional metadata via _lobstertrap: Supports declared-versus-detected intent inspection and audit reporting.
• Production-grade tooling: Includes real-time dashboards, audit logs, CLI utilities, and lightweight static Go binary deployment.
How Veea would like it presented: Lobster Trap is the floor, not the ceiling. Use it as the trust layer your project builds on top of, including policy packs for HIPAA, SOC2, or finance, drift monitoring, multi-agent permission systems, governance dashboards, and enterprise security workflows.

Access to Technology:

Lobster Trap is MIT-licensed and free.

Three ways to start:

• Standalone: Clone, run make build, then start with ./lobstertrap serve.
• Inside Native.Builder: Already packaged into lablab's Native.Builder.
• Pre-built static binaries: Linux, Windows, and macOS builds with no Go toolchain required.
No API keys, signups, rate limits, or cloud dependency required.

